Functions

bound_coord

This function was created specifically to see which are the maximum or minimum values for the latitudes and longitudes of the data. This way one can see where the data is located

bound_coord <- function(dataset, bound = max, coord = 'lat') {
  # The function prints the max and min values of the coordinates of the start and end positions.
  # bound is a function, can be max() or min(), coord can be the latitude (lat) or longitude (lon).
  
  if (coord == 'lat') {
    
    df <- select(dataset, start_lat, end_lat) %>%
      mutate(end_lat = na_if(end_lat, 0), start_lat = na_if(start_lat, 0))
    
    print(bound(df$start_lat, na.rm = TRUE))
    print(bound(df$end_lat, na.rm = TRUE))
    
    
  } else if (coord == 'long') {
    
    df <- select(dataset, start_lng, end_lng) %>% 
      mutate(end_lng = na_if(end_lng, 0), start_lng = na_if(start_lng, 0)) %>% 
      arrange(desc(start_lng), desc(end_lng))
    
    print(bound(df$start_lng, na.rm = TRUE))
    print(bound(df$end_lng, na.rm = TRUE))
  
  
  } else {
    
    stop('variable `coord` is not lat nor long')
  }}

distance_lat_lon

This function gives the displacement as a function of the initial and final coordinates, that is, the distance between two points in the surface of a sphere with the earth radius.

distance_lat_lon <- function(lat_1, lon_1, lat_2, lon_2) {
  
  rad_earth <-  6371 #km
  
  # Convert to radians
  
  theta_1 <- lat_1*pi/180 
  theta_2 <- lat_2*pi/180
  phi_1 <- lon_2*pi/180
  phi_2 <- lon_2*pi/180
  
  # Use formula for displacement
  
  displacement <-  2*rad_earth*asin(sqrt(sin((theta_2-theta_1)/2)^2+cos(theta_2)*cos(theta_1)*sin((phi_2-phi_1)/2)^2))
}

Answers to the Guiding questions

  • We can see that the majority of the data is located around Chicago, near the Michigan Lake. The range of latitudes is [ 41.55,42.18] The range of longitudes is [-88.16,-87.3]

  • It is important to highlight that some rows dont have the station names, however they still contain information about the location of the trip

  • In this case the data can be biased depending on the season of the year its been analized, for example, people can ride bycicles more oftenly on summer than on winter. In this case, the data corresponds to the last year. Also, we can notice that the positions of the stations can differ significantly. This makes me think that the stations position is a variable that needs to be carefully treated for analysis. Therefore we should consider rideable_type, times and dates of the rides, duration and position to distinguish the members, we will use the stations, but acknowledging that theres an important amount of data missing.

  • I believe theres a limitation of the data because theres not rider_id, so we dont know if multiple rides were made by different people or the same person.

  • Its ok to simply analyze the data publicly since the dataset doesnt contain any information about people or other sensible information. Furthermore, the data is public, so anyone should be able to access it

  • The I dont think there are any problems with the data, it is not clean, and there are a lot of empty spaces when it comes to the stations. I also need to check if the other columns are complete.

  label = c('Avg. 1.59', "Avg. 1.52"),
  member_casual   = c('casual', 'member'),
  x = c(1.59, 1.52)
)


#Histograms of displacement for casuals and members:
ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = displacement_km, y = ..density..)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = 'darkblue') +
  xlim(0,12) +
  facet_wrap(~member_casual, labeller = as_labeller(c('casual' = 'Casuals', 'member' = 'Members'))) + #Labels of facets
  geom_text(data = dat_text, mapping = aes(x = 1.65, y = 0.5, label = label), hjust = 'left', size = 4) +
  geom_vline(data = dat_text, aes(xintercept = dat_text$x), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = 'Displacement [km]',
       y = 'Density',
       title = 'Displacement made of casuals and members for each trip.') +

The peaks in these month distributions caught my attention, however I havent found a strong argument that explains them. Basically I would expect 4 peaks per month due to a weekly cycle, on the other hand , I would also expect an increase in bicycle usage on holidays, but theyre not that common. Other explanations may be:

  • Paydays

  • Government benefit

  • Holidays that I dont know

  • Weather

  • Other cyclical events.

  • Error making the plot

Top casual stations

Now Im going to use the information to evaluate which are the stations where casual users start their trips the most. For that purpose, Ill group the data by stations, counting the members and casuals for each. Then, Ill make a list of the stations with higher casual/member ratio (for those stations with more than 1000 users, because focusing on stations with less than approximately 3 users per day can be a waste of resources).

top_casual_stations <- df %>%
  select(start_station_name, member_casual) %>% 
  group_by(start_station_name) %>%
  summarise(members = sum(member_casual == 'member'),
            casuals = sum(member_casual == 'casual')) %>% 
  filter((members+casuals) >= 1000) %>%
  mutate(casual_member_ratio = casuals/members) %>% 
  arrange(desc(casuals/members))
